# Overview

This readme contains an (1) overview of the repos, (2) instructions to run them, (3) known bugs, (4) results, (5) info about dataset and (6) related works at the bottom.

## 1. Repo Overview

repo1, repo2, repo3 are all open-source repos for depression detection online. They each have the structure:  
repoX/Original-Open-Source-Repo-Title-From-Github/files  
where files includes the original files, some of which have been modified due to bugs.

Repo3 is the repo I had the most success with (and successfully debugged) which features two main directories:  
**daic\_woz\_process**  – this is the directory that pre-processes the DAIC-WOZ dataset  
**DepAudioNet\_reproduction** – this is the directory that processes the cleaned, preprocessed data

## 2. Instructions to Run
Note that I had significant bugs with the open source code-bases in repo1 and repo2, so they are not functional despite using the instrucitons listed in their respective readmes. It could be a dependency or hardware issue or slight discrepancy in pre-processing/data cleaning and the model code. Below are instructions for running repo3, which I've been able to run successfully. 
#### **Running repo3**

*Note that this runs on OSCAR Open on Demand (OOD). Due to the size of the dataset, you will need to run on some kind of virtual machine (VM) with significant memory and GPU ability. If you’re not using the OSCAR system at Brown University, replace references to OOD with a suitable VM*

**(1) running the preprocessing script**

Navigate to OOD Desktop (so that you can easily/quickly run interactive apps with GUI displays) – this automatically has functionality for what you would normally enable X11 forwarding and include \-X for

myenv   
conda activate repo3-preprocess  
cd thesis/repo3/daic\_woz\_process

\# ensure that the paths are what you expect in   
\# daic\_woz\_process/config\_files/config.py

python \-m run

\# this should take 5-10 mins to run on 2 GPUs (longer on 1 GPU)and should say \# ‘Finished Processing’ when complete

**(2)** **running the model training experiment** 

interact \-X \-q gpu \-t 2:00:00 \# requests a GPU w/ X11 fwding enabled for 2 hrs  
myenv   
conda activate repo3\_model  
cd thesis/repo3/DepAudioNet\_reproduction

\# ensure that the experiment details are what you expect in   
\# DepAudioNet\_reproduction/exp\_run/config\_1.py  
\# note the difference between the [built-in config params](https://github.com/adbailey1/DepAudioNet_reproduction/blob/ed09d52f426600b79d253e225bc4160bda1db8ca/exp_run/config_1.py#L13) and the one [listed on](https://github.com/adbailey1/DepAudioNet_reproduction/blob/main/README.md) \# [the readme](https://github.com/adbailey1/DepAudioNet_reproduction/blob/main/README.md) used to preproduce paper results

\# run the experiment w/ the intended configuration using this line:  
python3 main1.py train \--validate \--cuda \--position=1

If you need to delete a half-trained model & want to start from scratch (rather than loading from a checkpoint)  
\# this will remove the model and all the artifacts (e.g. logs) from   
\# the previous run. WORKSPACE\_MAIN\_DIR path is set in  
\# repo3/DepAudioNet\_reproduction/exp\_run/config\_1.py  
rm \-r WORKSPACE\_MAIN\_DIR/exp\_run/

### About Data Pre-processing

An older version of this repo processed the data according to this paper: [**Gender-Aware Estimation of Depression Severity Level in a Multimodal Setting**](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/9534330)  
But this version is no longer being used, since all the open-source repos I found had related preprocessing / data cleaning steps required to run on their setup

Follow this link for information on how to connect to [Connecting to OSCAR](https://docs.ccv.brown.edu/oscar/connecting-to-oscar/remote-ide) 

**Visual modalities pre-processing**

**Facial Landmarks:** 

1. Scale the Z-coordinate by first removing its average value (calculated over all the time steps), from all the time steps  
2. Scale the coordinates so that the mean distance of each point from the origin of the coordinate system is 1  
   1. The paper is ambiguous but I’m plotting the origin as the tip of the nose for the xy coordinates and the average z value for the z coordinate  
      ![][image2]  
3. Compute the euclidean distance between all the possible 2278 point pairs  
4. Append this to the scaled coordinates of the facial landmarks, getting a vector of length 2482

**Headpose** 

1. re-size (Tx,Ty,Tz) by dividing all of them by 100\.  
2. Since 30 Hertz makes it a lot of time steps, we down-size all the visual data modalities to 5Hz. We have adopted a zero-tolerance strategy towards time steps with no tracking success (where the success indicator is 0), and discard all such time steps. We take this decision, as we are wary of introducing any artifacts into the attribute space of the modality.   
   1. Note: their frame data is at 30 fps  
3. pad each of the ocular modality time series data with zeroes along the time axis, to have a uniform length of 10000 time steps for each of the data point. 

**Eye gaze data  \- none**   
**Facial action unit data- none**

**Auditory modalities pre-processing**

* Processed using the code from the original paper I am re-implementing

**Text modalities pre-processing**

* Remove informalisms  
* Compute 512 vector sentence embedding for each utterance, where each utterance is a continuous block of participant speech \> 1 second

**Preprocessing design limitations:**  
Right now I am saving the padded pre-processed data which uses unnecessary memory due to padding but because of convenience/ease of loading the data in it’s fully processed state, we choose this trade off 

## 6. Related Work

### Promising Papers to Re-Implement

[Multi-modal Depression Estimation based on Sub-attentional Fusion](https://paperswithcode.com/paper/multi-modal-depression-estimation-based-on) \[2022\]

* Multimodal  
* Convolutional Bidirectional LSTM backbone  
* 53 ★ on github  
* Uses DepAudioNet (the paper listed below) as their backbone for speech processing  
* Results: 0.89 precision and 0.70 F1-score in detecting major depression and 4.92 MAE in estimating the severity  
* Attention-based fusion module consistently outperforms conventional late fusion approaches and achieves competitive performance compared to the previously published depression estimation frameworks, while learning to diagnose the disorder end-to-end and relying on far fewer preprocessing steps.

**Why this paper is useful to my thesis:**  
It shows competitive accuracy (.7 F1 accuracy compared with .77 state of art) with minimal preprocessing and feature engineering, **which makes this model more practical/efficient for widespread use?**  
**Is this necessarily true?** 

Excerpts from the paper:

* Our proposed subattentional fusion model outperforms other data fusion techniques and yields competitive performance for MD estimation, while featuring far less feature engineering and data preprocessing than previously published approaches, for the purpose of a more accessible end-to-end automated depression assessment.  
* By observing the first two models, which are ConvBiLSTM with and without GB, one can notice a huge reduction of gender accuracy difference of around 7.3%. This signifies the seriousness of the role that the gender bias phenomenon plays in the acoustic features and how critical it is to handle it during the audio preprocessing stage.  
* Visual features, on the other hand, show no problem of gender bias with a gender accuracy difference of less than 1%, which is also understandable as one can imagine how challenging it is for a person to distinguish a participant’s gender solely based on the 68 3D facial key points.  
* decreased tendency of gender accuracy difference in multi-modal model can be discovered, implying that the more different modalities are fused, the lower this acoustic gender bias phenomenon shows up. This is the fact that by fusing variant data modalities, the model can learn diverse feature from different input sources and balance the gender bias  
* Finally, with the Sub-attentional ConvBiLSTM model trained on AVT modality, the lowest gender accuracy difference 0.35% is achieved, and thus it has the highest sensitivity in gender depression estimation over 82% accuracy in both genders.

DepAudioNet \- [Gender Bias in Depression Detection Using Audio Features](https://paperswithcode.com/paper/raw-audio-for-depression-detection-can-be) \[2020\]

* Only uses raw audio features   
* Uses data re-distribution you & other fair ML concepts to mitigate harmful effects of bias  
* 66 ★ on [**github**](https://github.com/adbailey1/DepAudioNet_reproduction) **– use this link**  
* Their [preprocessing github is here](https://github.com/adbailey1/daic_woz_process)  
* show that gender biases in DAIC-WOZ can lead to an overreporting of performance

### Understanding Model Architectures of Promising Related Work

Understanding the architecture in the Wei et al. paper: Multi-modal Depression Estimation based on Sub-attentional Fusion

ConvBiLSTM

2 engineering tricks to improve performance:

* Multipath uncertainty-aware score distributions learning:  
  * Converts ground truth categorical labels into soft label score distributions (from \[0, 1, …, X\] for X categories to a distribution of scores)  
* Sharpness Aware Minimization  
  * Second order optimization technique to find the global maxima/minima quickly for faster convergence

**Modality 1: auditory**  
Uses DepAudioNet backbone, which uses 1D CNN layers & LSTM layers to  
Transforms LSTM layers into BiLSTM  
Enables the applicability to a 3D input format by using 2D-CNN layers

**Helpful Resources / Notes:**  
Second order optimization – uses information from the second derivative about the global minimum/maximum to quickly converge to the optimal extrema ([helpful article](https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/328492/the-actual-role-of-second-order-optimization-as-oppose-to-first-order-optimizati))
